{"title_page": "Blood donation restrictions on men who have sex with men", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Discrimination sidebar|expanded=Policies}}\nMany countries have laws that prohibit donations of [[blood donation|blood]] or tissue for [[organ transplant]]s from [[men who have sex with men]] (MSM), a classification of males who engage or have engaged in sex with other males, irrespective of their [[Gay sexual practices|sexual activities with same-sex partners]] and of whether they [[Sexual identity|identify themselves]] as [[bisexual]] or [[gay]]. Temporary restrictions are sometimes called \"deferrals\", since blood donors who are found ineligible may be found eligible at a later date. However, many deferrals are indefinite meaning that donation are not accepted at any point in the future, constituting a [[de facto]] ban. Even men who have monogamous relations with their same-sex partner are found ineligible.\n\nRestrictions vary from country to country, and in some countries practice of protected sex or periods of abstinence are not considered. The restrictions affect these men and, in some cases, any female sex partners. They do not otherwise affect other women, including [[women who have sex with women]]. The [[United States Food & Drug Administration]] (FDA) asserts that the one year deferral window is \"supported by the best available scientific evidence\",<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usnews.com/news/articles/2015-12-21/fda-lifts-ban-on-blood-donations-from-gay-and-bisexual-men|title=Gay and Bisexual Men Can Soon Donate Blood \u2013 but There's a Catch|website=US News & World Report|access-date=12 June 2016}}</ref> but amidst the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]], it relaxed the deferral period to three months for MSM and women who have sex with MSM.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Zaveri |first1=Mihir |last2=Taylor |first2=Derrick Bryson |title=F.D.A. Relaxes Blood Donation Guidelines for Gay Men and Others |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/02/health/fda-blood-donations-coronavirus.html?smtyp=cur&smid=fb-nytimes&fbclid=IwAR3xq0qZh1h50nFCeejBr9PN7EhoBl-oKy3VlinSgWrM70EH8zJuaXy5n94 |accessdate=2 April 2020 |work=The New York Times |date=2 April 2020}}</ref> These changes are expected to stay in effect after the virus ends.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.fda.gov/news-events/press-announcements/coronavirus-covid-19-update-fda-provides-updated-guidance-address-urgent-need-blood-during-pandemic|title=Coronavirus (COVID-19) Update: FDA Provides Updated Guidance to Address the Urgent Need for Blood During the Pandemic|last=Commissioner|first=Office of the|date=2020-04-02|website=FDA|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> In Canada, the deferral period was decreased to 3 months in June 2019.<ref name=\"CAReport\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.blood.ca/sites/default/files/CBS-AR2019-en.pdf|title=Canadian Blood Services Annual Report 2018-2019|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=18 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nMany [[LGBT]] organizations view the restrictions on donation as based on [[homophobia]] and not based on valid medical concern since donations are rigorously [[HIV test|tested]] to rule out donors that are infected with known viruses such as [[HIV/AIDS|HIV]], [[Hepatitis B]], and [[Hepatitis C]]. They state the deferrals are based on stereotypes.<ref name=\"Schoettes\">{{cite news|title=Blood Donations Questions|last=Schoettes|first=Scott|date=December 2012|newspaper=Adelante Magazine}}</ref> Proponents of the lifetime restriction defend it because of the asserted risk of false negative test results<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/jeff-stier/blood-for-sale_b_52046.html |title=Blood for Sale |accessdate=5 April 2008 |last=Stier|first=Jeff |date=13 June 2007 |publisher=HuffingtonPost.com, Inc}}</ref> and because the MSM population in developed countries tends to have a higher prevalence of HIV/AIDS infection.<ref name=\"unaids2006\">UNAIDS 2006 report on the global AIDS epidemic, [http://data.unaids.org/pub/GlobalReport/2006/2006_GR_CH05_en.pdf Chapter 05], June 2006</ref> The UK government advisory committee, SABTO, stated in 2013 that \"the risk of transfusion of HIV infected blood would increase if MSM were allowed to donate blood\".<ref name=\"telegraph1aug2013\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/health/healthnews/8441054/Homosexual-men-allowed-to-give-blood-but-sex-banned-for-decade.html |title=Homosexual men allowed to give blood but sex banned for decade |work=Telegraph|date= 10 April 2011|last1=Bloxham |first1=Andy }}</ref> In July 2017 however, the UK government reduced the one year deferral window to three months, to take effect in the following months, resulting from SABTO's updated conclusions that \"new testing systems were accurate and donors were good at complying with the rules\". Furthermore, [[NHS Blood and Transplant]] are in the process of investigating how possible it is for MSM, depending on degree of risk, to donate without even the three-month deferral.<ref name=bbcjul17>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/health-40669950 |title=Blood donation rules relaxed for gay men and sex workers |accessdate=28 August 2017 |date=23 July 2017 |publisher=BBC.co.uk}}</ref> NHS has said that there is currently a limited amount of data on effective ways of conducting such risk assessments, and that the initial steps of scoping, evidence gathering and testing will potentially take up to two years to complete.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nhsbt.nhs.uk/news/scientific-review-offers-chance-for-more-people-to-give-blood/|title=Scientific review offers chance for more people to give blood|website=NHS Blood and Transplant|language=en|access-date=19 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nAdvocates for change to MSM prohibitions point out that screening of donors should focus on sexual behavior as well as [[safe sex]] practices since many MSM may always have protected sex, be [[monogamy|monogamous]], or be in other low risk categories.<ref name=Schoettes/><ref name=\"telegraph1aug2013\" /> Some groups in favor of lifting the restrictions support a waiting period after the blood is donated when the donor is considered to have had behavior considered higher risk, and before it is used, to match the blood bank's window of testing methods.<ref name=Schoettes/> While HIV is reliably detected in 10 to 14 days with RNA testing, older testing methods provide accuracy for only up to 98% of positive cases after three months.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.sfaf.org/hiv-info/testing/hiv-test-window-periods.html|title = HIV Test Window Periods|date = 2014|accessdate = 19 February 2015|website = San Francisco AIDS Foundation|publisher = San Francisco AIDS Foundation}}</ref>\n\nSince 1982, the risk for HIV infection transmitted via transfusion has been almost eliminated by the use of questionnaires to exclude donors at higher risk for HIV infection and performing screening tests with highly sensitive equipment to identify infected blood donations. According to the 2015 surveillance report by Canadian Blood Services, the risk of HIV transfusion-transmitted infection was fairly low: in 1 in 21.4 million donations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blood.ca/sites/default/files/External_Surveillance_Report_2015.pdf|title=Surveillance Report 2015|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=18 November 2019}}</ref> [[Contaminated haemophilia blood products|Contaminated blood]] put [[hemophilia|haemophiliacs]] at massive risk and severe mortality, increasing the risk of common surgical procedures. People who contracted HIV from a contaminated blood transfusion include [[Isaac Asimov]], who received a blood transfusion following a cardiac surgery.\n\n==HIV/AIDS==\n{{Main|Men who have sex with men#HIV/AIDS}}\nIn many developed countries HIV is more prevalent among [[men who have sex with men]] (MSM) than among the general population.<ref name=\"unaids2006\"/>\n\nIn the United States the population most affected by HIV includes gay, bisexual, and other MSM.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cdc.gov/hiv/group/msm/index.html|title=HIV and Gay and Bisexual Men|date=12 November 2019|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=18 November 2019}}</ref> Of the 38,739 new HIV diagnoses in the US and dependent areas in 2017, 70% consisted of adult and adolescent gay and bisexual men.<ref name=\":2\" /> Although approximately 492,000 sexually active gay and bisexual men are at high risk for HIV, there are more tools to prevent HIV than ever before.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== Current situation ==\n=== List of countries with their stand on MSM blood donors ===\n[[File:MSM Blood Donation Map New.svg|thumb|500x500px|Blood donation policies for men who have sex with men\n{{legend|LightGreen|Men who have sex with men may donate blood; '''No deferral'''}}\n{{legend|Lime|Men who have sex with men may donate blood; '''No deferral, except for blood transfusions'''<sup>1</sup>}}\n{{legend|Khaki|Men who have sex with men may donate blood; '''Temporary deferral'''<sup>1</sup>}}\n{{legend|Salmon|Men who have sex with men may not donate blood; '''Permanent deferral'''<sup>1</sup>}}\n{{legend|#CCCCCC|No Data}}\n<sup>1</sup>No restriction in Israel, Belgium and the United States of America if last MSM activity was before 1977.]]\n[[File:Female partners of men who have sex with men blood ban by country.svg|thumb|right|500px|Blood donation policies for female sex partners of men who have sex with men\n{{legend|LightGreen|Female sex partners of men who have sex with men may donate blood; No deferral}}\n{{legend|Khaki|Female sex partners of men who have sex with men may donate blood; Temporary deferral}}\n{{legend|Salmon|Female sex partners of men who have sex with men may not donate blood; Permanent deferral}}\n{{legend|#DCDCDC|No Data}}]]\n\nThis list shows countries that had restrictions on blood donors.<ref name=\"Seed\">{{cite journal|journal=Transfusion|title=No evidence of a significantly increased risk of transfusion-transmitted human immunodeficiency virus infection in Australia subsequent to implementing a 12-month deferral for men who have had sex with men|first1=Clive R.|last1=Seed|first2=Philip|last2=Kiely|first3=Mathew|last3=Law|first4=Anthony J.|last4=Keller|volume=50|issue=12|pages=2722\u20132730|doi=10.1111/j.1537-2995.2010.02793.x|date=December 2010|pmid=20663106|url=https://zenodo.org/record/897682}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bloodservices.ca/CentreApps/Internet/UW_V502_MainEngine.nsf/resources/Reports/$file/McLaughlin_Report.pdf|title=Mclaughlin Report on Risk Management for Canadian Blood Services|date=31 January 2007|publisher=McLaughlin Center for Population Health Risk Assessment, University of Ottawa|page=28|accessdate=25 May 2008}}</ref> Most national standards require direct questioning regarding a man's sexual history, but the length of deferral varies.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Country \n! Deferral for MSM \n! Deferral for female<br>sex partners of MSM \n! class=\"unsortable\" | Ref(s)\n|-\n| {{flag|Albania}}\n|data-sort-value=\"0\" {{Yes|No deferral}}\n|data-sort-value=\"0\" {{Yes|No deferral}} \n|\n|-\n| {{flag|Algeria}}\n| {{No|Indefinite}}\n| \n| {{citation needed|date=April 2014}}\n|-\n| {{flag|Argentina}}\n|data-sort-value=\"0\" {{Yes|No deferral}}\n|data-sort-value=\"0\" {{Yes|No deferral}}\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.argentinaindependent.com/currentaffairs/newsfromargentina/heath-ministry-removes-ban-on-homosexual-blood-donors/|title=Health Ministry Removes Ban on Homosexual Blood Donors|author=Matthew Corb|publisher=The Argentina Independent|date=16 September 2015|access-date=17 September 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181219134401/http://www.argentinaindependent.com/currentaffairs/newsfromargentina/heath-ministry-removes-ban-on-homosexual-blood-donors/|archive-date=19 December 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{c