75|work=\u4e2d\u56fd\u7ecf\u6d4e\u7f51|date=31 December 2015|access-date=26 July 2017|publisher=re-published by cnr.cn|language=Chinese}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chinatelecom-h.com/en/regulatory/announcements/a170607.pdf|title=RESIGNATION OF DIRECTOR AND CHANGE OF IMPORTANT EXECUTIVE POSITION|date=7 June 2017|access-date=26 July 2017|publisher=China Telecom}}</ref>}}}}\n|parent = [[China Telecommunications Corporation]]\n|owner= [[China Telecommunications Corporation]] (70.89%)\n|homepage = [http://www.chinatelecom-h.com chinatelecom-h.com]\n| footnotes=in a [[consolidated financial statement]]<ref name=ChinaTelecom2016AR>{{cite web|url=http://www.hkexnews.hk/listedco/listconews/SEHK/2017/0406/LTN20170406631.pdf|title=2016 Annual Report|date=6 April 2017|access-date=26 July 2017|publisher=China Telecom}}</ref>\n}}\n{{Chinese|title=China Telecom Corp., Ltd.|s=\u4e2d\u56fd\u7535\u4fe1\u80a1\u4efd\u6709\u9650\u516c\u53f8|t=\u4e2d\u570b\u96fb\u4fe1\u80a1\u4efd\u6709\u9650\u516c\u53f8|p=Zh\u014dnggu\u00f3 Di\u00e0nx\u00ecn G\u01d4f\u00e8n Y\u01d2uxi\u00e0n G\u014dngs\u012b|order=st|altname=China Telecom|s2=\u4e2d\u56fd\u7535\u4fe1|t2=\u4e2d\u570b\u96fb\u4fe1|p2=Zh\u014dnggu\u00f3 Di\u00e0nx\u00ecn}}\n'''China Telecom Corp., Ltd.''' is a Chinese telecommunications company.<ref>{{cite web |url = https://www.bloomberg.com/quote/728:HK/profile |title = 728 Profile & Executives \u2013 China Telecom Corp Ltd \u2013 Bloomberg |website = bloomberg.com |accessdate = 22 August 2012}}</ref> It is one of the listed companies of [[State-owned enterprise|state-owned]] [[China Telecommunications Corporation]]. Its [[H share]] traded in the [[Stock Exchange of Hong Kong]] since 15 November 2002.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hkex.com.hk/eng/stat/smstat/chidimen/cd_hmb.htm|title= List of H Share Companies (Main Board) |date=30 June 2017|access-date=26 July 2017|publisher=Hong Kong Stock Exchange}}</ref> It is a constituent of [[Hang Seng China Enterprises Index]], the index for H share of state-controlled listed companies.\n\nChina Telecom was a brand of China Telecommunications Corporation, but after marketization of China, the state-owned enterprise spin off the brand and operating companies as a separate group, floating it in the Stock Exchange of Hong Kong.\n\n{{as of|2017}}, it had 153&nbsp;million customers that are using [[China Telecommunications Corporation]]'s internet service, which 134&nbsp;million of them belongs to the listed company, China Telecom Corp., Ltd.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://finance.eastmoney.com/news/1355,20180126825905028.html|script-title=zh:\u4e2d\u56fd\u7535\u4fe1\u5168\u56fd\u5bbd\u5e26\u7528\u6237\u8d851.5\u4ebf \u79fb\u52a8\u7528\u6237\u51c0\u589e\u521b\u65b0\u9ad8|date=26 January 2018|access-date=11 February 2017|work= \u7ecf\u6d4e\u53c2\u8003\u62a5|author=\u4faf\u4e91\u9f99|via=[[East Money]]|language=zh-cn}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nChina Telecom Corp., Ltd. was incorporated on 10 September 2002 as a limited company<ref name=ChinaTelecom2016AR/>{{rp|133}} in order to float some of the assets of the group in the stock exchange, specifically the wireline\ntelecommunications business in Shanghai, Guangdong, Jiangsu and Zhejiang, as well as other assets from the parent company.<ref name=ChinaTelecom2016AR/>\n\nIn 2003, it acquired business in Anhui, Fujian, Jiangxi, Guangxi, Chongqing, Sichuan, as well as other assets for {{CNY|link=yes|46&nbsp;[[1,000,000,000|billion]]}}.<ref name=ChinaTelecom2016AR/> In 2004, it acquired business in Hubei, Hunan, Hainan, Guizhou, Yunnan, Shaanxi, Gansu, Qinghai, Ningxia and Xinjiang and other assets for {{CNY|27.8&nbsp;billion}}.<ref name=ChinaTelecom2016AR/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB108184972487481191|title=China Telecom Deal To Lift Public's Stake|date=April 13, 2004|accessdate=September 28, 2018|newspaper=The Wall Street Journal |url-access=subscription |first1=Evan|last1=Ramstad|first2=Loretta|last2=Ng}}</ref> In 2007, it acquired three companies China Telecom System Integration, China Telecom Global and China Telecom (Americas) for {{CNY|1.408&nbsp;billion}}.<ref name=ChinaTelecom2016AR/> In 2008 the business in Beijing (as China Telecom Group\nBeijing) was acquired for {{CNY|5.557&nbsp;billion}}.<ref name=ChinaTelecom2016AR/>{{rp|134}} In 2011, e-commerce business and video media business were acquired by China Telecom's subsidiaries E-surfing Pay and E-surfing Media. However, subsidiary E-surfing Media was sold back to the parent company in 2013.<ref name=ChinaTelecom2016AR/>{{rp|134}} In 2012, digital trunking business was acquired from sister company [[Besttone Holding]] (a listed company of Shanghai Stock Exchange) for {{CNY|48&nbsp;million}}.<ref name=ChinaTelecom2016AR/> In 2013, China Telecom (Europe) was acquired from the parent company for {{CNY|278&nbsp;million}}.<ref name=ChinaTelecom2016AR/>\n\nIn 2015, China Telecom formed a joint venture {{ill|China Tower|zh|\u4e2d\u570b\u9435\u5854}} with fellow state-owned telecommunication companies [[China Mobile]] and [[China Unicom]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ft.com/content/9870c994-72ee-11e5-bdb1-e6e4767162cc |title= China telecoms operators pool $36bn in assets |date=15 October 2015 |access-date=28 September 2018 |newspaper=Financial Times |first=Gabriel |last=Wildau |url-access=subscription}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.hkexnews.hk/listedco/listconews/SEHK/2015/1014/LTN20151014732.pdf|title=Discloseable transaction in relation to the disposal of telecommunications towers and related assets|date=14 October 2015|accessdate=28 September 2018|publisher=China Telecom|location=Hong Kong|via=Hong Kong Exchanges and Clearing website}}</ref> China Tower, which was the largest telecommunications tower group by revenue, became a separate listed company in 2018.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.ft.com/content/96640eda-960f-11e8-b67b-b8205561c3fe |title= China Tower raises most in an IPO globally since 2016 |date=2 August 2018 |access-date=28 September 2018 |newspaper=Financial Times |first=Emma |last=Dunkley |url-access=subscription}}</ref> China Telecom, China Mobile and China Unicom were remained the largest clients of China Tower {{as of|2018|lc=y}}.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.scmp.com/business/companies/article/2155994/china-tower-worlds-largest-mobile-phone-tower-company-kick-years|title=China Tower, world\u2019s largest mobile phone tower company, to kick off year's biggest IPO next Wednesday|date=19 July 2018|accessdate=28 September 2018|newspaper=South China Morning Post|publication-place=Hong Kong}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2015, [[Chang Xiaobing]], former chairman of [[China Unicom]], became the chairman of China Telecom as well as the parent company of the listed company, China Telecommunications Corporation.<ref name=BBC2015/><ref name=resign2015>{{cite press release|url=http://www.hkexnews.hk/listedco/listconews/SEHK/2015/0824/LTN20150824372.pdf|title=resignation of director|date=24 August 2015|accessdate=28 September 2018|publisher=China Telecom|via=Hong Kong Exchanges and Clearing website}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.hkexnews.hk/listedco/listconews/SEHK/2015/0901/LTN201509011203.pdf|title=APPOINTMENT OF CHIEF EXECUTIVE OFFICER AND PROPOSED APPOINTMENT OF DIRECTOR|date=1 September 2015|accessdate=28 September 2018|publisher=China Telecom|via=Hong Kong Exchanges and Clearing website}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.hkexnews.hk/listedco/listconews/SEHK/2015/1023/LTN20151023300.pdf|title=List of directors and their role and function|date=23 October 2015|accessdate=28 September 2018|publisher=China Telecom|via=Hong Kong Exchanges and Clearing website}}</ref> While {{ill|Wang Xiaochu|zh|\u738b\u6653\u521d (\u4e2d\u56fd\u7535\u4fe1)}}, who served the two positions, was appointed to the positions in China Unicom.<ref name=resign2015/><ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.hkexnews.hk/listedco/listconews/SEHK/2015/0901/LTN20150901915.pdf|title=List of directors and their role and function|date=1 September 2015|accessdate=28 September 2018|publisher=China Unicom (Hong Kong)|via=Hong Kong Exchanges and Clearing website}}</ref> However, Chang was under investigation for corruption in December 2015 and resigned.<ref name=BBC2015>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/business-35203675|title=China Telecom chief resigns amid investigation|date=31 December 2015|accessdate=28 September 2018|work=BBC News Services}}</ref> He was sentenced in 2017.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.scmp.com/tech/enterprises/article/2096382/former-china-telecom-boss-chang-xiaobing-sentenced-six-years|title=Former China Telecom boss Chang Xiaobing sentenced to six years for corruption|date=31 May 2017|accessdate=28 September 2018|work=South China Morning Post|publication-place=Hong Konf}}</ref>\n\n== Network ==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+Frequencies used on China Telecom Network in China\n|-\n! Frequency !! Frequency Width !! Protocol  !! Notes\n|-\n| 850&nbsp;MHz (825-835;870-880)|| 2x10 MHz || [[CDMA]]/[[LTE (telecommunication)|LTE]] ||\n|-\n| 1800&nbsp;MHz (1860-1880;1765-1785)|| 2x20 MHz || [[LTE (telecommunication)|LTE]]  || \n|-\n| 2100&nbsp;MHz (1920-1940;2110-2130)|| 2x20 MHz || [[CDMA]]/[[LTE (telecommunication)|LTE]]  || \n|-\n| 2300&nbsp;MHz (2370~2390) <br>Band 40 || 20&nbsp;MHz || [[TD-LTE]] || indoor use only\n|-\n| 3.5 GHz (3400~3500) || 100&nbsp;MHz || [[5G NR]] || Trial\n|}\n\n\n===Expansion outside Mainland China===\nChina Telecom (Europe) on 23 October 2008 said it would expand its Asian-European services, aiming to increase its market share in Europe.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2008-10/24/content_10244252.htm |title=China Telecom to spread Asian-European services|publisher=Xinhua News Agency|date=23 October 2008 |accessdate=28 September 2018 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6AX4cRAn9?url=http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2008-10/24/content_10244252.htm |archivedate=8 September 2012 |df=dmy-all |location=London}}</ref> China Telecom (Europe) became part of the listed portion of the China Telecom Group, China Telecom Corp., Ltd. in 2013.\n\nIn 2008, China Telecom acquired China Unicom (Macau). The subsidiary was also renamed to {{ill|China Telecom (Macau)|zh|\u4e2d\u570b\u96fb\u4fe1\uff08\u6fb3\u9580\uff09}}<ref name=ChinaTelecom2016AR/>{{rp|151}} In 2015 China Telecom (Macau) acquired the [[4G LTE]] license from the Macau S.A.R. authority.<ref>{{cite press release|url=https://www.gcs.gov.mo/showNews.php?DataUcn=86772&PageLang=C|script-title=zh:\u7d93\u71df\u63a1\u7528\u9577\u671f\u6f14\u9032\u6280\u8853\uff084G\uff09\u7684\u516c\u5171\u5730\u9762\u6d41\u52d5\u96fb\u4fe1\u7db2\u7d61\u53ca\u63d0\u4f9b\u76f8\u95dc\u7684\u516c\u7528\u5730\u9762\u6d41\u52d5\u96fb\u4fe1\u670d\u52d9\u724c\u7167\u7684\u516c\u958b\u62db\u6a19\u4e4b\u7af6\u6295\u7d50\u679c |date=9 March 2015|accessdate=28 September 2018|publisher=Direc\u00e7\u00e3o dos Servi\u00e7os de Regula\u00e7\u00e3o de Telecomunica\u00e7\u00f5es|publication-place=Macau|language=zh-hant}}</ref> The 4G service started in the same year.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.tdm.com.mo/c_news/radio_news.php?id=275921|script-title=zh:\u4e2d\u570b\u96fb\u4fe1 (\u6fb3\u9580) \u555f\u52d54G|date=25 November 2015|accessdate=28 September 2018|department=R\u00e1dio Macau|publisher=Teledifus\u00e3o de Macau|language=zh-hant, yue|author1=\u5ed6\u51ac\u97fb|author2=\u9ec3\u5049\u9d3b}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2011, China Telecom formed a strategic partnership with German software group SAP to offer a cloud-based version of SAP's business software to small and medium companies in China.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/1b1f345a-7fdf-11e0-b018-00144feabdc0 |title=SAP-China Telecom deal to offer cloud-based services in China |newspaper=Financial Times |date=17 May 2011 |access-date=28 September 2018 |first=Paul |last=Taylor |url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\nChina Telecom was one of the bidders of the newly opened Myanmar Mobile licences' call for tender.<ref name=ref2013040505>\n    {{Cite news\n    |title = Vodafone, China Mobile eye Myanmar\n    |publisher = Investvine.com\n    |date = 5 April 2013\n    |url = http://investvine.com/vodafone-china-mobile-eye-myanmar/\n    |accessdate = 5 April 2013}}\n</ref>\n\n==Subsidiaries==\n{{updated|19 November 2018}}\n* China Telecom (Americas) Corporation<ref name=ChinaTelecom2016AR/>\n* China Telecom (Europe) Limited<ref name=ChinaTelecom2016AR/>\n{{expand list|date=July 2017}}\n\n==Equity interests==\n{{updated|31 December 2016}}\n* [[Besttone Holding]] (6.13%)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://static.sse.com.cn/disclosure/listedinfo/announcement/c/2017-04-22/600640_2016_n.pdf|title=2016 Annual Report|date=22 April 2017|access-date=26 July 2017|publisher=Besttone Holding|language=Chinese|page=35}}</ref>\n\n==Shareholders==\n{{updated|31 December 2016}}<ref name=ChinaTelecom2016AR/>{{rp|50}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Rank !! Name !! Chinese name !! Percentage !! Footnotes\n|-\n| 1 || [[China Telecommunications Corporation]] || \u4e2d\u56fd\u7535\u4fe1\u96c6\u56e2\u516c\u53f8 || 70.89% || Central Government-owned [[state-owned enterprise|SOE]], owner of A share\n|-\n| 2 || [[Guangdong Rising Assets Management]] || || 6.94% || Guangdong Government-owned SOE, owner of A share\n|-\n| 3 || [[JPMorgan Chase]] || || 2.19% || [[Long (finance)|Long position]] figure only, owner of H share\n|-\n| 4 || [[BlackRock]] || || 1.02% || Long position figure only, owner of H share\n|-\n| 5 || [[The Bank of New York Mellon]] || || 0.93% || Long position figure only, owner of H share\n|-\n| 6 || Templeton Global Advisors || || 0.87% || Long position figure only, owner of H share\n|-\n| 7 || [[GIC Private Limited]] || || 0.86% || Long position figure only, owner of H share\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of telephone operating companies]]\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|http://www.chinatelecom-h.