{"title_page": "Tim Robinson (cartographer)", "text_new": "{{short description|British cartographer}}\n{{refimproveBLP|date=October 2010}}\n'''Tim Robinson''' (1935 \u2013 3 April 2020) was a writer and [[cartographer]]. Born in [[Yorkshire]], he studied mathematics at [[Cambridge University]]. After a career as a visual artist in [[Istanbul]], [[Vienna]] and [[London]] he settled in the [[Aran Islands]], off the coast of [[County Galway]], and began a detailed study of the landscape of the west of Ireland. He won two [[Irish Book Awards]] for his Connemara books.\n\nRobinson died in London on 3 April 2020 at the age of 85, due to [[COVID-19]].<ref>[https://www.rte.ie/culture/2020/0403/1128347-author-and-cartographer-tim-robinson-dies-from-coronavirus/ Author and cartographer Tim Robinson dies from coronavirus]</ref>\n\n==Works==\nRobinson produced maps of the Aran Islands, [[Connemara]], and [[the Burren]] in [[County Clare]]; these were published by Folding Landscapes, the imprint he and his wife M\u00e1ir\u00e9ad ran from their [[Roundstone, County Galway|Roundstone]] base. \n\nHis two-volume study of the Aran Islands, ''Stones of Aran'', is a much-praised compendium of topographical and culture lore, described by [[Michael Viney]] as \"One of the most original, revelatory and exhilarating works of literature ever produced in Ireland.\"<ref>Michael Viney, [http://www.lilliputpress.ie/listbook.html?id=157 review of ''The Stones of Aran''], [[Irish Times]].</ref> ''Stones of Aran: Pilgrimage'' follows the form of a coastal exploration, while ''Stones of Aran: Labyrinth'' explores the interior.\n\nHis most recent work{{When?|date=April 2020}} was the publication of a three-volume study of Connemara: ''Listening to the Wind'', ''A Little Gaelic Kingdom'', and ''The Last Pool of Darkness''. He was a member of the Irish arts organisation [[Aosd\u00e1na]].\n\n==Awards==\nTim Robinson won two [[Irish Book Awards]]: the 2007 Argosy Irish Non-Fiction Book of the Year for ''Connemara: Listening to the Wind'' <ref>[http://www.irishbookawards.ie/PreviousWinners.aspx Irish Book Awards: Previous Winners] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111117085117/http://irishbookawards.ie/PreviousWinners.aspx |date=2011-11-17 }}</ref> and the 2011 International Education Services Best Irish-Published Book of the Year for ''Connemara: A Little Gaelic Kingdom''.<ref>[http://www.irishbookawards.ie/AwardDetails.aspx Irish Book Awards: 2011 Awards] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090525041617/http://www.irishbookawards.ie/AwardDetails.aspx |date=2009-05-25 }}</ref>\n\n==Principal publications==\n*''Stones of Aran: Pilgrimage'' ([[The Lilliput Press]], 1986)\n*''Connemara: A One-Inch Map, with Introduction and Gazetteer'' (Folding Landscapes, 1990)\n*''Stones of Aran: Labyrinth'' (Lilliput Press, 1995)\n*''Oile\u00e1in Arann: A Map of the Aran Islands, with a Companion to the Map'' (Folding Landscapes, 1996)\n*''Setting Foot on the Shores of Connemara'' ([[The Lilliput Press]], 1996)\n*''The Burren: A Map of the Uplands of North-West County Clare'' (Folding Landscapes, 1999)\n*''My Time in Space'' ([[The Lilliput Press]], 2001)\n*''Tales and Imaginings'' ([[The Lilliput Press]], 2002)\n*''Connemara: Listening to the Wind'' (Penguin Ireland, 2006)\n*''Connemara: The Last Pool of Darkness'' (Penguin Ireland, 2008)\n*''Connemara: A Little Gaelic Kingdom'' (Penguin Ireland, 2011)\n\n==Notes==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.foldinglandscapes.com/ Folding Landscapes website]\n*[http://nyrb.typepad.com/classics/2009/10/tia-tim-robinsons-aran.html A Different Stripe: Notes from NYRB Classics]\n*[http://www.librarything.com/author/robinsontim Library Thing, Tim Robinson]\n\n===Reviews===\n*[https://www.theguardian.com/books/2006/oct/07/featuresreviews.guardianreview4  review of ''Connemara: Listening to the Wind''] by [[Joseph O'Connor]], ''Guardian''\n*[https://www.theguardian.com/books/2005/may/14/featuresreviews.guardianreview34  review of ''Rock of Ages''] by [[Robert Macfarlane (travel writer)|Robert Macfarlane]], ''Guardian''\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Robinson, Tim}}\n[[Category:Aosd\u00e1na members]]\n[[Category:English geographers]]\n[[Category:English cartographers]]\n[[Category:Writers from Yorkshire]]\n[[Category:People from County Galway]]\n[[Category:English expatriates in Ireland]]\n[[Category:1935 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:Date of birth missing]]\n[[Category:Deaths from the 2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British cartographer}}\n{{refimproveBLP|date=October 2010}}\n'''Tim Robinson''' (1935 \u2013 3 April 2020) was a writer and [[cartographer]]. Born in [[Yorkshire]], he studied mathematics at [[Cambridge University]]. After a career as a visual artist in [[Istanbul]], [[Vienna]] and [[London]] he settled in the [[Aran Islands]], off the coast of [[County Galway]], and began a detailed study of the landscape of the west of Ireland. He won two [[Irish Book Awards]] for his Connemara books.\n\nRobinson died in London on 3 April 2020 at the age of 85, due to [[COVID-19]].<ref>[https://www.rte.ie/culture/2020/0403/1128347-author-and-cartographer-tim-robinson-dies-from-coronavirus/ Author and cartographer Tim Robinson dies from coronavirus]</ref>\n\n==Works==\nRobinson produced maps of the Aran Islands, [[Connemara]], and [[the Burren]] in [[County Clare]]; these were published by Folding Landscapes, the imprint he and his wife M\u00e1ir\u00e9ad ran from their [[Roundstone, County Galway|Roundstone]] base. \n\nHis two-volume study of the Aran Islands, ''Stones of Aran'', is a much-praised compendium of topographical and culture lore, described by [[Michael Viney]] as \"One of the most original, revelatory and exhilarating works of literature ever produced in Ireland.\"<ref>Michael Viney, [http://www.lilliputpress.ie/listbook.html?id=157 review of ''The Stones of Aran''], [[Irish Times]].</ref> ''Stones of Aran: Pilgrimage'' follows the form of a coastal exploration, while ''Stones of Aran: Labyrinth'' explores the interior.\n\nHis most recent work{{When?|date=April 2020}} was the publication of a three-volume study of Connemara: ''Listening to the Wind'', ''A Little Gaelic Kingdom'', and ''The Last Pool of Darkness''. He was a member of the Irish arts organisation [[Aosd\u00e1na]].\n\n==Awards==\nTim Robinson has won two [[Irish Book Awards]]: the 2007 Argosy Irish Non-Fiction Book of the Year for ''Connemara: Listening to the Wind'' <ref>[http://www.irishbookawards.ie/PreviousWinners.aspx Irish Book Awards: Previous Winners] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111117085117/http://irishbookawards.ie/PreviousWinners.aspx |date=2011-11-17 }}</ref> and the 2011 International Education Services Best Irish-Published Book of the Year for ''Connemara: A Little Gaelic Kingdom''.<ref>[http://www.irishbookawards.ie/AwardDetails.aspx Irish Book Awards: 2011 Awards] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090525041617/http://www.irishbookawards.ie/AwardDetails.aspx |date=2009-05-25 }}</ref>\n\n==Principal publications==\n*''Stones of Aran: Pilgrimage'' ([[The Lilliput Press]], 1986)\n*''Connemara: A One-Inch Map, with Introduction and Gazetteer'' (Folding Landscapes, 1990)\n*''Stones of Aran: Labyrinth'' (Lilliput Press, 1995)\n*''Oile\u00e1in Arann: A Map of the Aran Islands, with a Companion to the Map'' (Folding Landscapes, 1996)\n*''Setting Foot on the Shores of Connemara'' ([[The Lilliput Press]], 1996)\n*''The Burren: A Map of the Uplands of North-West County Clare'' (Folding Landscapes, 1999)\n*''My Time in Space'' ([[The Lilliput Press]], 2001)\n*''Tales and Imaginings'' ([[The Lilliput Press]], 2002)\n*''Connemara: Listening to the Wind'' (Penguin Ireland, 2006)\n*''Connemara: The Last Pool of Darkness'' (Penguin Ireland, 2008)\n*''Connemara: A Little Gaelic Kingdom'' (Penguin Ireland, 2011)\n\n==Notes==\n<references />\n\n==Ex